To capture the concept of completeness, five COIL variables seem particularly germane: the relative complexity of the cooperation problems the agreement addresses, the sheer length of the agreement, whether any appendices or annexes are included, the overall precision or ambiguity of agreement terms, and whether the agreement refers to existing international agreements. This last component regarding references has not been theorized. It could be argued references make a contract more complete as they may partially fill in incomplete terms (perhaps filling the role “precedent” plays in the domestic context);
26
 conversely, references may add further incompleteness by engaging a wider set of issues, goals, or other complications, trade-offs, and possible subsumptions.
